abstract: Spain, France and the Czech Republic also announced plans to investigate Google’s collection of data from wireless networks in their countries.
snippet: Spain, France and the Czech Republic also announced plans to investigate Google’s collection of data from wireless networks in their countries.
lead_paragraph: BERLIN — Officials in Spain, France and the Czech Republic announced plans on Thursday to investigate Google’s collection of data from wireless networks in their countries, raising the likelihood that the company could face sanctions in Europe.

headline.main: In Europe, Google Faces New Inquiries on Privacy

abstract: The surprising endorsement by the Federal Trade Commission of Google’s deal for AdMob follows Apple’s purchase of Quattro Wireless, an AdMob rival.
snippet: The surprising endorsement by the Federal Trade Commission of Google’s deal for AdMob follows Apple’s purchase of Quattro Wireless, an AdMob rival.
lead_paragraph: SAN FRANCISCO — After an intensive six-month review, Google won approval from the Federal Trade Commission on Friday for its $750 million acquisition of the mobile advertising company AdMob.

headline.main: U.S. Approves Google’s Deal for AdMob
headline.print_headline: U.S. Approves Google’s Deal For AdMob

abstract: In a reversal of regulatory fortune, Google has won approval from the Federal Trade Commission for its $750 million acquisition of the mobile advertising company AdMob.
snippet: In a reversal of regulatory fortune, Google has won approval from the Federal Trade Commission for its $750 million acquisition of the mobile advertising company AdMob.
lead_paragraph: In a reversal of regulatory fortune, Google has won approval from the Federal Trade Commission for its $750 million acquisition of the mobile advertising company AdMob, The New York Times’s Brad Stone reported on Friday.

headline.main: Regulators Approve Google Deal for AdMob

abstract: Six countries have joined Germany in a move that may force the company to disclose what data its employees collected from unsecured wireless networks.
snippet: Six countries have joined Germany in a move that may force the company to disclose what data its employees collected from unsecured wireless networks.
lead_paragraph: BERLIN — In a sign that Europe is taking an increasingly unified line on Internet privacy, six European countries have joined Germany in asking Google to preserve data it improperly collected from unsecured wireless networks as part of Street View, its photo-mapping service, the company said Friday.

headline.main: Wider European Scrutiny of Google on Privacy
